## querySelector()

`querySelector()` is used to select HTML elements.

### Select by ID

```javascript
document.querySelector("#title");
```

Example:

```html
<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
```

The `#` symbol represents an ID.

---

### Select by Class

```javascript
document.querySelector(".box");
```

The `.` symbol represents a class.

---

### Select by Tag

```javascript
document.querySelector("h1");
```

Selects the first `<h1>` element on the page.

---

## addEventListener()

`addEventListener()` is used to listen for events such as clicks, keyboard input, and form submissions.

### Syntax

```javascript
element.addEventListener("event", function() {
    // code to execute
});
```

---

## Click Event Example

HTML:

```html
<h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
<button id="btn">Change Text</button>
```

JavaScript:

```javascript
let button = document.querySelector("#btn");

button.addEventListener("click", function() {
    document.querySelector("#title").innerText =
    "AI Healthcare App";
});
```

### Result

Before clicking:

```text
Hello
```

After clicking:

```text
AI Healthcare App
```

---

## Why Use addEventListener()?

Instead of:

```html
<button onclick="changeText()">
```

developers prefer:

```javascript
button.addEventListener("click", function() {
    // code
});
```

Benefits:
- Keeps HTML and JavaScript separate
- Makes code cleaner
- Easier to manage large projects
- Allows multiple event listeners

---

## Key Takeaways

- `querySelector()` selects HTML elements.
- `#` is used for IDs.
- `.` is used for classes.
- `addEventListener()` listens for events.
- Click events allow users to interact with webpages.
- JavaScript can update webpage content without reloading the page.

